com.inqwell.any.client

Class AnyAttributeSet

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.inqwell.any.AbstractComposite
      • com.inqwell.any.AbstractMap
        • com.inqwell.any.PropertyAccessMap
          • com.inqwell.any.AnyMap
            • com.inqwell.any.AnyPMap
              • com.inqwell.any.client.AnyAttributeSet
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, Composite, Map, Serializable, Cloneable

    public class AnyAttributeSet
extends AnyPMap
implements Cloneable
    Encapsulate the Java AttributeSet in the Any framework. This class acts as a wrapper for MutableAttributeSet implementations. As a Map it supports named children but these children must themselves be AnyAttributeSets.

    The enclosed Java AttributeSet does not know about children but does support a link to a parent style, through which it attempts to resolve attribute requests that it itself does not define. When AnyAttributeSet children are added to an AnyAttributeSet the underlying Java object in the child has its resolve parent set to that in this, so the Any hierarchy is used as a way to create the style hierarchy. By establishing an Any hierarchy of AnyAttributeSet instances then, assuming a naming convention where ever these styles are used, the root of the tree represents a style context.

    Although a Map the contains(key) and get(key) methods do not enjoy their usual relationship - contains(key) returns true if either this or the underlying attribute set contains the given key. Special keys are converted to their JDK equivalent name/value pairs in the attribute set - contains(key) doesn't check for this so will always return false in this case.

      • copyFrom

        public Any copyFrom(Any a)
        Establish a new AttributeSet. A number of possibilities are acceptable for the argument:
      • AnyAttributeSet: The AttributeSet enclosed in a becomes the AttributeSet of this. If the implementation of that AttributeSet is clonable then it will be cloned, otherwise it will be shared between the two AnyAttributeSets. If the AttributeSet is cloned and the Any parent of this is a AnyAttributeSet then the AttributeSet resolve parent is set to the object contained in the parent AnyAttributeSet.
      • Map: The map is processed according to the well-known key values for style attribute keys. See AnyDocument.

  • clone

    public Object clone()
             throws CloneNotSupportedException
    The Any hierarchy is cloned and the enclosed Java attribute set is cloned also. This means, respectively, (normally) a deep copy and a shallow copy.

    In general, it is expensive to clone the root of a style hierarchy, but this is an unlikely thing to do. Cloning a style leaf is more likely, especially to add auxiliary information, and its OK to do this.
